value.0: "Life grows dull without you. I need your spark to help me feel that life might have some purpose. May I come with you again?"
"Being brought back to life leaves me feeling empty. Do as you will; abandon me if you must."
"I shall do my best to help you stay alive, though my own existence is a burden."
"Our enemy whispers in my head. How foolish. As if I would respond to such an unnatural creature."
"This is a beautiful grove of trees. I can hear them whispering to me, as if they are welcoming me home."
"The dwarves are going to be enraged when they find their hall has been flooded with magma."
"I sense some restless spirits here, but this is a beautiful place to be laid to rest."
"Oh, my! Look at that tree! How absolutely amazing. For this alone it is worth saving the keep!"
"The crowds of people in this place are enough to drive me mad. Let's not stay here long."
"I know it's silly, but any tavern called the Mossy Tree will hold a special place in my heart."
"Too bad these people don't spend as much time taking care of the world the gods made them as they do in this temple."
"They are destroying each other, as all perversions of nature eventually must."
"I understand why you bought this place, but I do hope you'll buy a few plants to liven it up."

"This place makes me wonder if Sir Becket is truly evil, or just a fool with poor taste."

value.0: "Then I shall go to the giant tree in the north keep. I would like to speak to it again."
"What can I do to better please you?"
"I guess I can just fight, but I should at least use my buff spells before attacking."
"I will do as you say. I like a mixture of spellcasting and melee."
"I wasn't really doing any good."
"I'm not sure what I can do."
"As you wish."
"Like the wind through the trees."
"I shall do as you say. I was not very good at it anyway."
"I will probably just end up beating on it with a stick, but if that's what you want."
"As you wish. How far would you have me stand?"
"I will do so."
"If you say so. Just remember to back me up."
"I dislike rushing to the attack anyway. Well, most of the time."
"Do as you must."
"I will do my best, though I make no promises."
"I see. What manner of buffing spells would you have me use?"
"And what is my target?"
"So be it!"
"What shall I cast, then?"
"I can do that. Are you certain?"
"And what is my target?"
"Was there anything else then, friend?"
"So be it!"
"It will be nice to return to my own form again."
"It is always pleasing to travel for a while in the form of a beast. Which creature would you have me be?"
"Now that I am at full power, love, we shall smash our enemies into dust!"
"Ha! You remembered. Very well, I shall do this."
"A sleek and dexterous form. It shall be so."
"What did you wish to speak about?"
"Is there anything else you would ask of me?"
"I'm alright. Does this armor make me look fat? Oh, never mind."
"Do you want anything else?"
"I had a dream last night that I lay bare in the woods, covered in butterflies. It was... an unusual dream."
"I can sense that there are cats around, yet I have not seen any. I wonder where they are?"
"The wildlife around here is suffering. The invaders tax the land and hunt all creatures. Sad, really."
"One of the birds here keeps telling me I look pretty. I'm glad animals do not have the same outlook on life as we do."
"Every once in a while I catch you smiling. That lifts my spirits, a little."
"Things are not so terrible, though I could always use some encouragment."
"I do not like this darkness that blinds my eyes. If you could just direct me to a temple..."
"A few scratches and bruises, but nothing to be terribly concerned about."
"My wounds are serious, but I still have life left in me."
"There is little life left in me. Soon I shall go back to the embrace of the earth."
"A toxin is beginning to cripple me. Please, we must find an antidote."
"I have the shakes. I fear that my body has some kind of disease."
"I have my home now. When my seed was planted, I accepted responsibility for that grove, for the entire area, actually."
"You will always have me, so long as you want me and treat me well. You know you have my bond in this."
"I would like you to work with me to set up an area around my grove, protected from the landowners, the hunters and the foresters."
"There is a good chance they would not like it, but with me there to protect it and you backing me up legally, we might be able to accomplish something lasting. What do you think?"
"I am glad you feel that way, because if you win this election I would like you to work with me to set up an area around my grove, protected from the landowners, the hunters and the foresters."
"There is a good chance they would not like it, but with me there to protect it and you backing me up legally, we might be able to accomplish something lasting."
"I would love to know your mind on this. What do you think?"
"Everything I knew is now dead and gone. Even if new trees and creatures could return there, they would not remember me. I will honor my old home by being a better protector of my new home."
"For as long as you want me around. I can think of no better place to be than at your side."
"I don't know for sure, but I doubt it. I think I will have to find a new home, perhaps near one of the beautiful northern lakes. I like the cold, rugged beauty of the nearby mountains."
"I am glad you feel that way, because if you win this election I would like to work with you to set up an area protected from the landowners, the hunters and the foresters."
"There is a good chance they would not like it, but with me there to protect it and you backing me up legally, we might be able to accomplish something lasting."
"I would love to know your mind on this matter."
"You are probably right. You have enough on your mind right now. I shouldn't be pressing political issues on you when you're busy trying to get elected."
"Well, come to think of it, that would seem to be the perfect time for issues. I think you're really becoming a proper politician, if you already know how to dodge a question like that."
"That is a choice you will have to make every day. A ruler makes rules for <his/her> people to follow. But I see now that it is not an important issue for you. I will let it alone then."
"I guess you probably wouldn't, though I think the guilds will only have as much power as you allow them."
"So you would actually help me in this? Oh, <FirstName>, you are too kind to me. I don't know why you put up with me the way you do. No one else would care for this ugly monster."
"Is there some bitter core to your personality that must lash out at everyone? One more foul word out of you and I might have to leave."

Comment.value: Kaidala goes to the giant tree.

value.0: Kaidala stares at you with sad, pained eyes. "As you wish."
"Let's go. I don't want to speak to you again for a while. If you do not wish to be left alone here, consider treating me better."
Her eyes narrow dangerously. "And what exactly is worse than being an ugly monster?"
Her jaw drops open, then she starts to laugh. "I don't know whether to hate you or love you for a joke like that."
She smiles and gives a little giggle. "You're terrible. But I do like you for that."
She nods. "I guess that's an answer."
She smiles and hesitantly touches your face with her soft hand. "I'll do my best."
"But that is exactly what I fear. I have had a taste of what life can be like with friends. I fear death less than I fear being alone."
"I don't know about that. I still haven't made up my mind."
"But we should get going. There is still much to do before I can settle down again."
She smiles. "That is kind of you to say. Thank you so much."
She smiles hesitantly and touches your face with her soft hand. "Some say that love must be blind. I guess they must be right."
"We should get going again. There is much to be done."
"If you would really want to. I would certainly welcome you as a visitor, and should you choose to stay... but that is the future."
"It is not my home any longer. Everything I knew is now dead and gone. Even if new trees and creatures could return there, they would not remember me. I will find a true home, someday."
"I will do what I can to help you, but if you win this election, I'm sure there will be plenty of other people to help you. I doubt you will need me anymore."
"That is not to say that I would refuse to help you. If you have real need, I will always be there for you."
"You are so hard to understand. I don't know if I will ever really be able to know you. Not as I had once hoped."
"We should be going now. I do hope that you are able to reach your goals. Then maybe you will help me reach mine."
"Perhaps you have heard of the Gai Zan? They are a cult of zealots who believe that the emperor is the chosen of the gods and will someday become a god himself."
"Their one purpose in life is to hunt and destroy any who might become a danger to their ruler."
She shrugs. "It is hard to relive those moments." She sighs and turns away.
"The Gai Zan are led by a supposed prophet. This prophet claimed that there was one from my forest who would rise up and assist the evil one destroy the emperor."
"It was nothing that I did. The Gai Zan are led by a supposed prophet. This prophet claimed that there was one from my forest who would rise up and assist the evil one to destroy the emperor."
"I'm not sure who the evil one was supposed to be, but they take those sort of prophesies very seriously. They came to the village that lay close to my forest and began torturing the peasants."
"Some of the peasants knew I lived in the woods, from past... encounters. They convinced the Gai Zan that I must be the one from the prophesy."
"I should be mad at them, but they were trying to save their own lives, and the lives of their families. I don't blame them. I blame the perpetrators of the crime."
"That hardly seems likely. I would have no reason to cause the emperor harm."
"One of the peasant girls that I had once helped ran to warn me. As soon as the zealots realized that I was a nymph and could possibly kill them or control them, they made their choice."
"They must have used magic to enhance their fire, for I have never seen a blaze move so fast or with so much purpose towards a goal. But... but you know the rest."
She begins to weep. "I cannot speak anymore of that night. It is too hard. Even now I feel the flames licking at my face and burning my hair."
"Yes, yes. That is for the best."
"I am sorry. You must hate me for being so soft. I shall try to be strong for you. I know you do not need any more burdens."
"You make it sound so easy, yet I am sure there must be things in your past that haunt you. You wanted me to tell you; I did not bring it up."
"We should be going now."
"I thank you for that. I don't know that you could prevent it, though. Still, it helps having you around."
"We should be going now. Thanks for listening to me."
"Trip ran into the Gai Zan one time also. They didn't taste too bad, for zealots."
"Considering that as part of their lifestyle they refuse to bathe, I'm surprised you could get close enough to eat them."
"When you're hungry, you're hungry. What else can I say?"
"A zealot does not think rationally. It is their trademark that they always overreact to a situation."
"I don't know. Kaidala is quite a troublemaker. Imagine if she could kill you with a glance? I'm already frightened she might smother me with affection!"
"And you had better stay afraid, Calibast. I have ample means of dousing your fire!"
"That life seems so far removed from where we are today. I can't say that I truly miss it, though. Except my tree. I miss my tree with an ache that I cannot even begin to describe."
"I never really had any friends. Not like I do now." She smiles at you as she says this.
"It was a different life, and I was a different person. I didn't really miss the fact that I had no friends, most of the time. I could always use my charms to ensnare a little company."
"If you are simply going to insult me, then don't ask me to share my past with you."
"None of the forest creatures could really be called my friends. Nymphs don't tend to live close to each other. Too much competition."
"Dryads are too flighty to be good friends, though we did share some time together. The animals were probably my closest friends, but they live at a different speed. It was hard to become close."
"The closest I ever came to a friendship was with a druid. But I don't think you could even count him as a friend."
"It wasn't really much of a relationship. I suppose I had a strange sort of rapport with him, but it's actually kind of embarrassing."
"As a druid, he knew what my kind was like, and not wanting to expose himself to the dangers of being around a nymph, he cast a protective spell on his encampment against fey."
"He also avoided any part of the forest that he thought I might occupy, and the animals took it as a game to try to help him."
"I wouldn't call it hurting him... no. It was other things that he was trying to avoid."
"At first I was merely curious about him, but when I realized that he was actively avoiding me, I began to try in earnest."
"Finally, after many attempts, I was able to trick him into inviting me into his encampment."
"I figured that he would only speak to animals, and I wanted to appear as an animal he would be curious about, so I concentrated all of my magical energies and turned into a chicken."
She giggles. "Why, thank you, <FirstName>. I bet you would make some quality poultry yourself. But do you understand my reasoning?"

value.0: "It is, isn't it?" She grins. "We should get back to solving your problems now. We'll talk, later."
"I am afraid this might seem like a strange question, my friend, but are you going to win this election?"
"If that is how you truly feel, then I will make no long-range plans for staying here."
"With you, it is sometimes very difficult to decide what is a joke and what is serious."
"That is all I needed to know. Let's continue on."
"And would you like me to continue to be your companion, even once you are the ruler here?"
"I know what I desire, but I need you to tell me how you feel. Just tell me, would you like me to stay or go, once you are the ruler of this keep."
"That is unfortunate. I was hoping for something more encouraging than that. Very well, let us continue on."
"Then would you do something for me? Before I fled the fire that destroyed my home and my face, I had determined to die with my tree."
"You would be right, but my family was hunted and killed, and my mother left me with dryads before she was caught. The dryads taught me the magic of their trees, how to gain strength from them."

"I became attached to a beautiful oak, tall and strong. The dryads said that the tree chose me because I had similar attributes to an oak. But that was long ago. I am no longer strong and proud like an oak."
"As the fires closed in, I felt a peculiar sensation... a rubbing of the bark beneath my hands. When I pulled my hand away, a single acorn fell from above, directly into my open palm."
"I knew then that my tree was bidding me to flee the fires. It was saying goodbye."
"Even a tree has the basic, natural urge to see something of its life continue through offspring. I could feel its love for me, more than ever before."
"I took the seed and protected it, but now I am ready to plant it. There is a grove of trees in the hills; I have heard them speaking to me."
"Would you take this acorn and plant it in the center of the grove, that I might make this my new home?"
"There is no other time. It takes time for a tree to grow, even with my help. Please, it is now or never."
"If you cannot figure that out, then I have nothing further to say to you."
"All I ask is that you plant it. I will do the rest. Is that so much to ask of a friend?"
"Then perhaps I have made a mistake. Please forget I ever said anything about it. Let us continue our journey." Kaidala turns sadly away.

value.0: "And what conclusions have you arrived at? Can you see yourself settling down in one place, or do you see yourself as the perpetual wanderer? Will you grow tired of this keep and want to move on?"
"Do. It is important. Think about it right now. Would you consider that in the near future? Or do you see your destiny as a perpetual wanderer? Will you grow tired of this keep and want to move on?"
Kaidala blushes, but then laughs. "Men! You're just about as bad as I used to be."
"Let us be on our way then. Too much to do, in so little time."
She blushes. "Oh, no. I was just trying to make a few decisions. Nothing to worry about... right now."
"Then perhaps we can search together? Maybe we could even help each other capture a true love."
"Ladies! You need look no further! Trip is here with all the love you could ask for and then some!"
Kaidala laughs, which sends Trip into a pout. She then strokes his head and gives him a peck on the cheek, which brightens his outlook considerably.
"That is... too bad. Still, things might change once you win this election."
"I see what you mean. I shall have to think on that. If you do settle I will need to make my own plans."

She smiles and nods. "They all say that. Maybe it is even true. Anything else?"
She cocks a questioning eyebrow. "There are differing standards on intelligence. Are there other attributes you would look for?"
She nods and sighs, "I should have expected that. Is there anything else?"

value.0: "You have committed yourself to this place of violence. I can feel the deaths that have come here, yet, I do see a beauty, different from the settlements of the south."
"That is sad, <FirstName>. Perhaps you are simply refusing to see it."
"Open your eyes and your heart, put away your preconceived notions and allow yourself to experience something without a jaded view, for once. Otherwise, you will always be disappointed."
"I am sorry. That was a bit preachy, wasn't it? I just felt like it needed to be said. We should continue now."
"I... I don't know what to say, <FirstName>. No one has ever said such kind words to me before. Even when I was beautiful."
"When I first met you, I thought you must have been a messenger of the gods. I thought you would smite me down for becoming such an ugly creature."
"But you are beautiful in so many ways and each time I become disheartened by my lack of beauty, you say something that lifts me and makes my spirits soar. I am so attracted... I mean, I..."
"When I first met you, I thought you were just one of those ordinary people. You weren't frighteningly ugly, yet, you certainly didn't match up with my ideal of beauty either."
"When I first met you, I thought you were part of the nightmare that my life had become. Nymphs fear that which is not pleasing to the eye."
"Now I know that you are truly beautiful, no matter what you look like on the outside. Not that I find you unappealing. I... I mean... oh, now I feel like an imbecile."
"Fie! I am supposed to be quick and witty, yet I stumble over my tongue when I speak to you this way. Let's get back to what we were doing. Maybe I can organize my thoughts better."
"Perhaps that is what it is. I look at these people, and where I expect to find fear and despair, I see hope and determination."
"I find their attitudes to be... inspirational. Suddenly I don't feel so sad. I feel... hope. Something I have not felt in a long time."
"We can continue now. I feel... better."

value.0: "This hermit lives all alone, just as I used to. His friends are animals and insects, not other people."
"For a while, perhaps, but not for too long. I do not think I could go back to such an existence."
"There are moments of peace in such a life, but there are also stretches of maddening loneliness. No one could accuse the hermit of being in a state of utter bliss."
"I am not sure I could do so again. I am simply too used to being around friends.
"What a lonely existence. You could be surrounded by people who care for you, yet feel totally alone."
"I am sorry you feel that way. I believe that friendship is the only coin worth saving. Other things in life can be traded away, but friendship should be protected."
"We had better get moving again."
"Thank you, <FirstName>. I wouldn't be here if you hadn't been such a good friend to me."
"We had better get moving again. Thank you for listening to me. Sometimes I just need a shoulder to lean on."
"Poor, lonely nymph. And I suppose that if we ever have to leave you behind, you'll need to be put out of your misery."
"Jaboli, I know that somewhere, deep inside that rough exterior, you are also a friend to me."
"I don't think you are perceptive enough to claim to know what is deep inside me."
"We could always open you up and have a look!"
"Trip is your friend, Kaidala! I will stay close to you and keep you safe."
"Um... thanks, Trip."
"Unless there is great danger or peril nearby. Then Trip will run, yes! He will flee because danger is no friend to poor Trip!"
"I am your friend, Kaidala, even if you fear my flamin' head."
"Thank you, Calibast. I'm sure someday I will get over it. Just don't hug me.... please."
"<StartAction>[Sigh]</Start> If I had a copper for every time I've heard that..."
"I certainly used to, but now... now I am not sure that I could ever go back to such an existence again."

"Oh, thank you, <FirstName>. You have been so good to me. So much more than just an old friend... But let us speak of this later. We need to get back to what you were doing."

value.0: "I am sorry about that creature. I believe that my bond with the powers of nature opened a door for my worst nightmare to become reality."

"But most of my powers have been recovered now, <FirstName>. I might never be able to kill people with a simple glance, but my connection to nature, as a druid, will allow me to turn into a treant again."
"Just tell me if you wish me to use that power. And, <FirstName>, thank you for staying with me and protecting me. I hope we have an entire lifetime to get to know each other better."
"Perhaps we shall even try out the quaint, mortal tradition of marriage. Even a nymph can settle down, I suppose."
"I love you, <FirstName>. Now let's go kill our enemies and make a place that's safe for true love!"
"I think I saw something watching me, with hunger and desire in its eyes. Suddenly death chills me more than I thought it would. I shall try to do better to help us survive."
"Do not be angry with me, please. I am sorry. I shall wait here."
"I guess I could use a little more rest, but don't leave me here long, please."
"Of course. I shall do as you command."
"I like to hear that... that you need me. It gives life a little more meaning."
"Someone else has asked for my help. I am sorry I cannot work with you right now."
Kaidala ignores you, whispering quietly to her tree and then giggling absent-mindedly.
"Nature thrives when we strive for harmony. We should always work towards that goal."
"Will you please stop drooling on me, Trip? Are you sure that your natural form wasn't a rat? You certainly didn't retain many of your human traits."
"Trip was a man, and most of my worst habits came from my time as a human. I think that is why Trip was so disliked by everyone back then."
"Oh, I'm sorry. I shouldn't be so harsh I guess."
"It is all right. Trip is used to people not understanding him. Actually, Trip did spend a short time in his rat form, once."
"I always wondered about that. I've never seen you in that form."
"Trip is rather afraid of taking that shape again... in case the evil mage is still looking for me."
"Evil mage? What do you mean?"
"Trip was hungry once, yes, very hungry, and I found a tower, dark and scary. I thought I should transform into a rat, sneak in and find something to eat."
"Trip was captured by the owner of the tower, a powerful mage, who mistook me for a real rat. He thought I seemed very smart, for a rat, and decided to keep me as his familiar."
"Sorry <master/mistress>. Trip will try to ignore the constant badgering of the nymph!"
"The what? How is this my fault, you scrawny, mangy, flea-bitten rat? Oh, never mind."
"Yes. This story doesn't seem terribly plausible, Trip."
"Trip didn't know what it would do, but I knew I didn't want to stay with a mage, so I bit him on the finger and fled."
"But the mage didn't just let you go, did he?"
"No, he cast spells at Trip and tried to capture him. One spell was a ghostly cat following me really close, so I was terribly frightened."
"I didn't know what to do, so I turned into Trip's favorite form, this one. The spell cat went right past Trip and didn't recognize me."
"And that is why, years later, you refuse to ever take your rat form?"
"You can never be too cautious with mages. They can be very tricksy!"
"I don't understand this. They were here when I went to sleep last night. Where could they have gone?"
"Did you lose something, Kaidala? Trip finds things really well. Maybe he could find something for you?"
"I had a pair of stockings for when my feet got cold, but I can't find them."
"Oh... Trip doesn't know about that." Trip tries to hide one of his hands behind his back as surreptitiously as possible.
"Trip! Do you have my stockings? Your feet are covered in hair; what could you possibly need my stockings for?"
"Trip doesn't know what you are talking about! Do you know, Mister Rags?" Trip swiftly brings his hand out, which is covered in black cloth with small holes and decorations stuck to it.
"I don't know what she is ranting about, Mister Trip," Trip says in a low, gravelly voice.
"What... is... that?"
"Hello, pretty lady! I'm Trip's new friend, Mr. Rags. Would you like to be my friend too?"
"No! I don't want to be your friend! Argh! Now I'm talking to my own stocking!"
"That's all right, Kaidala. Trip knows what it is like to have strange friends that others don't understand or appreciate."
"I don't have voices in my head or invisible friends. I am not like you!"
"Trip wasn't talking about the voices. Trip was talking about you and <FirstName>."
"Where is my other stocking?" Kaidala gives Trip an evil look.
"What would you need the other stocking for? One stocking would do you no good." Trip's head droops and he glances guiltily around.
"Trip! Where is it?"
"Trip is sorry, but I did not think Kaidala would be needing the other stocking... and Trip was soooo hungry!"
"Never mind, Trip." Kaidala heaves a heavy sigh.
"You can play with Mr. Rags any time you want to, Kaidala."
"Joy."
"Jaboli, do you think you will ever find love? Not that I'm saying you're difficult to love, but what would you look for in a life mate?"
"I do not concern myself with things like that. If I do find love someday, then I suppose I shall be happy, but until then, I will live joyfully without such worries."
"But that seems so sad. A life without love... it just seems so empty."
"I hope you are not going to suddenly burst into song here. I tire of the idea that life must be filled with romance or be horribly dull."
"But you are beautiful. There must be some who would find you attractive. I'm sure if you tried..."

Comment.value: if PC has gotten into romance plot with Kaidala.

value.0: "You are not listening to me, Kaidala! It is not that I have not had any opportunities; it is that I am not interested!"
"Well, you don't have to yell at me! I was just wondering and trying to show an interest in your life."
"You were just trying to stick your nose in something that does not concern you, and I would thank you to mind your own business."
"I will then! See if I ever send a handsome man your way again!"
"Send a... as if I would be interested in your cast-offs! Please, if he was interested in you, don't do me any favors. He would obviously have severely impaired judgement!"
"How dare you?!? Why I ought to..."
"No!"
"Sometimes you have to let us work out our differences."
"You have neither the brains to challenge me, nor the power. What are you going to do... deflect my magic with your impressive bosom?"
"I'm a lot tougher than you give me credit for! I could... wait, do you really think my bosom is impressive?"
"Are you kidding? No, I can see that you aren't. I think we have exhausted the possibilities of this conversation!"
"What is this? Another hair? Jaboli, do you think you will ever stop shedding like this?"
"What are you talking about, child? I take excellent care of myself. I do not shed!"
"You do too. I find your hair in everything! It's been in the food, on my clothes, in the bed rolls... everywhere! I was brushing my hair yesterday and I found one of your hairs in my hair."
"You are just imagining it. Probably because you are jealous."
"And what exactly do I have to be jealous about? You think I want to have hair covering my entire body? I would be shaving constantly."
"I don't know... I think you might look cute with whiskers."
"Trip had whiskers. Did you think he was cute?"
"An interesting point and one I find much amusement in. There are similarities between you and Trip. You both whine a lot and neither of you is as useful as one could hope."
"I will remember that next time you need healing."
"I can't believe you would say that! And how can you be so cruel to Trip when he's dead, Jaboli?"
"Actually, I miss some of Trip's antics. Even though he could be a pest, at least he was funny."
"I was only teasing her. Actually, I miss some of Trip's antics. Even though he could be a pest, at least he was funny."
"I miss him too. <StartAction>[sigh]</Start> I hope he found greater happiness in the afterlife. I hope he got rid of the voices in his head."
"He's probably stolen the pearls from Mistress Death's eyes and accidently swallowed them."
Kaidala grins. "Can you imagine if he got to go to Suhili's paradise? With pearly gates and streets of gold, he wouldn't know what to do. He'd end up lugging around a ton of pavement."
Jaboli stares off into nothing for a moment. "I am sorry for my harsh words, Kaidala. I wish I had said some nicer things to Trip, when he lived."
"Me too. And you don't really shed so much. I shouldn't be so picky. I'll try to be more cheerful. We should get going now." They smile tentatively at one another, then look to you.
"Calibast, what has been your favorite adventure you've had with our group?"
"Do you remember the thief of hearts?"
She grins. "Yes. That was great fun. Do you remember where that happened, <FirstName>?"
"Quite a friendly village, Littlefield, so long as you minded your business and didn't ask too many questions. The thief was doing them a favor, if you ask me."
"Now there is a city with corruption problems. I thought the thief almost brought a note of respectability to a city full of vice and distorted lives."
"Ah, yes, the Grim Woods were dark and creepy. I thought the thief actually brought a little life to them. He wasn't any worse than the local lord."
"His thefts were daring, but he was still a thief. I don't feel too bad about bringing him to justice."
"We were paid well enough to bring him in. Still, sometimes I wonder if we did the right thing."
"Of course he was! He was using them to create magical elixirs to stop a plague. He only stole the organ of newly deceased people. I don't know what everyone was so upset about."
"Graverobbing is a serious offense in many places. People were horrified that when they would go to visit the grave site of a loved one, the bodies had been exhumed and desecrated."
"People are too sensitive. Much better to preserve the livin' than worry about a few corpses."
"From people who didn't need it! He kept quite a few peasants from starvin' to death, if I remember correctly!"
"I also notice he kept the greatest share of the treasure for himself."
"He was the one takin' all the risks, you cannae blame him for wantin' a fair reward. The very fact that he shared at all is more than can be said of most men."
"Women who wanted to be stolen! Many of them were slaves that he was freeing from horrible conditions. Some were young women who were being forced into unhappy marriages."
"I notice he only chose young, fairly good-looking women to *free* from their oppressors."
"You cannae blame the man for havin' decent taste. I mean, who wants to steal some ugly, old, crotchety grandmother? I did nae hear any of the young lasses complainin' about their treatment."
"We did manage to capture him, but not until he'd caused us quite a few problems. You remember the dungeon he trapped us in?"
"Oh, nobody blamed you for what happened. You know better than to get so far ahead of the group that we can't watch each other's backs now. We survived, so no harm done."
"Well, she couldn't be expected to understand proper adventurin' etiquette so soon. She didn't know she should wait for the thief to look for trip wires before headin' down that corridor."
"I felt like such a fool. I just realized something! I bet the reason why you liked that adventure so much was because of that room full of dryads!"
"You had better be believin' it. I've never encountered such an appreciative group of young ladies before."
"Well, they had been stuck down there with the thief for such a long time. I can't say I blame them, though they could have tried to control their enthusiasm."
"Well, we helped them escape and then they helped us trap the thief, so I can't say I regret a moment of it."
"Not that I know of, and brownies aren't anywhere near as fun. There are a few satyrs though. If you like that kind of thing."
Calibast gives you a glare, then begins to laugh.
"Men!" <StartAction>[Sigh.]</Start>
"All right, enough reminiscing. Let's get some work done. I feel the need to kill something soon."
"My fault? If our lousy thief had been lookin' for traps instead of treasure, I might not have caught my foot on that trip wire! My fault indeed."
"I bet the reason why you liked that adventure so much was because of that room full of dryads!"
"Calibast? I have always thought of fire as a natural destroyer, yet you come from a home that is created by fire, correct?"
"True enough, darlin'. What's your point?"
"I was just wondering what your world could possibly be like. Is it a giant ball of flames, or is there anything similar to nature here?"
"Not like here, no. Our forests are giant crystalline structures that grow up from the obsidian earth. Our lakes are made of great pools of lava."
"That sounds absolutely horrifying! Are there none of the gentle sounds of nature, like the babbling of a brook, the wind whistling through the boughs of a tree?"
"Actually, the sound of the wind whistling through the crystalline forests is more beautiful than any sound I have heard on this plane. It is also the most dangerous."
"Sorry, I didn't mean to slow us down. I'll try to be quiet."
"Don't listen to <him/her>, Kaidala. If <he/she> could get rid of all conversation and make life just one big battle after another, none of us would ever speak again."
"Like ethereal music, played on hundreds of thousands of instruments. I have only heard it a few times. We don't venture close to the forests often, due to the dangers."
"To hear the music of the forest, one has to be standing near or in it. The wind will often cause numerous small crystals to break free and whip them at high speeds in any direction."
"So the falling of leaves could literally kill you?"
"It often does. And not only that, but sometimes an entire branch or tree will fall and fragment, sendin' a spray of crystals for miles."
"You may find this strange, but I actually think I like that. There is a certain beauty to creations of nature that are incredibly beautiful, yet wonderfully deadly."
"Is that not what bein' a nymph is all about? I have heard tales of some nymphs that can kill just by lookin' at a fellow with her unearthly beauty."
"All nymphs can do that to some degree, with myself as the single exception. It doesn't work against all creatures, nor all males either. Nice point though."
"I do what I can to keep things interestin'."
"Not yet. I will come back for you."
"Yes. Please follow me."
"Never mind."
"I think we need to part ways."
"No, never mind."
"Wait here until I return."
"I need to go."
